# Project 08 — GNC / Monte Carlo Engagement Analysis

Proportional navigation guidance law implementation, 500-run Monte Carlo engagement
simulation, and full performance analysis of a missile homing on a maneuvering drone
target. Three PN variants implemented and compared. Outputs: miss distance
distribution, CEP, Pk curve, launch envelope heatmap, sensitivity analysis, ECM
robustness, and animated 3D trajectory.

## Overview

Guidance, navigation, and control (GNC) is the intelligence layer that separates a
ballistic projectile from a guided weapon. This project implements a True Proportional
Navigation (TPN) guidance law on a point mass missile model and characterizes
performance across 500 randomized engagements against a 3g maneuvering drone target.

The analysis pipeline is:

Point mass missile dynamics (Project 06 propulsion/drag)
→ True PN guidance law (LOS rate computation, seeker FOV, actuator lag)
→ Maneuvering target model (bang-bang evasion, 3g lateral acceleration)
→ Single engagement simulation with CPA detection
→ 500-run Monte Carlo (randomized geometry, heading, noise, wind)
→ Performance metrics: CEP50/90/95, Pk, launch envelope, sensitivity, ECM

Key result: TPN with N=5 achieves CEP50=374m and Pk=0.8% against a fully
maneuvering 3g drone target at randomized launch geometries spanning 1-8km range.
Performance is limited by the decoupled vertical channel and absence of end-game
guidance refinement — both documented modeling choices, not implementation errors.
TPN outperforms PPN by 8x in CEP50 on this engagement geometry.

