## Assumptions

- Point mass missile — no fin deflection, no autopilot, no angle of attack
- Vertical channel decoupled from PN lateral guidance
- Target acceleration perfectly known (used directly for APN; TPN ignores it)
- Seeker noise is Gaussian, uncorrelated — no colored noise or bias model
- Wind applied as constant velocity offset to missile velocity during guidance
  computation — no gust dynamics
- Thrust along velocity vector — no thrust misalignment
- Flat Earth, no Earth rotation
- Atmosphere: exponential density model, constant speed of sound 343 m/s
- Target altitude held perfectly constant — no altitude variation in evasion
- Lethal radius 20m — representative of a proximity-fuzed warhead

## Limitations

- **Decoupled vertical channel:** TPN omega_perp projection mixes vertical LOS
  rate into horizontal commands when missile velocity has a vertical component.
  The P-controller workaround is functional but not physically rigorous. A proper
  3D TPN implementation uses the full LOS rate vector without projection.

- **No end-game guidance refinement:** No time-to-go estimation, no terminal
  phase gain scheduling, no proportional navigation bias for target acceleration
  compensation in TPN. These are standard additions for real missile guidance.

- **Point mass model:** Lateral acceleration commands applied directly — no
  aerodynamic response, no autopilot lag beyond the first-order lag model.
  Full 6-DOF engagement simulation (coupling Project 06 to guidance) would
  require fin deflection → moment → angle of attack → lift force chain.

- **APN instability:** The (N/2)·a_t_perp term adds a large vertical component
  when target acceleration is primarily horizontal, fighting the altitude
  controller. Fix requires projecting a_t perpendicular to the LOS vector,
  not just perpendicular to missile velocity.

- **PPN altitude channel:** pure_pn() altitude fix applies gravity comp and
  proportional term using current missile/target positions, but the function
  was not validated across all Monte Carlo geometries. PPN is provided for
  comparison only.

- **50-run sensitivity analysis:** Sensitivity plots use 50 runs per parameter
  value — insufficient for smooth curves, but adequate for trend identification.

- **Flat miss distance distribution:** CEP50=374m with runs spanning 13m to
  1255m indicates high variance. The long tail is driven by unfavorable
  engagement geometries (head-on, tail-chase, extreme altitude error) where
  the guidance cannot converge before motor burnout.

